- "shining stars of the television world" refers to genres that have both higher than average viewership and higher than average ratings;
- "captivating more viewers" means having an average number of viewers greater than the overall average number of viewers across all genres;
- "earning higher ratings" means having an average rating greater than the overall average rating across all genres.

- "The smallest branch" refers to the season with the minimum number of episodes;
- "The grandest branches" refers to the seasons with more episodes;
- "Measures the popularity and appreciation" refers to the average number of viewers and average rating of the episodes.

- "stands tallest" refers to the episode with the highest rating and the highest total viewers;
- "most beloved and watched" refers to the highest rating and the largest audience;
- "hails from the most acclaimed season" refers to the season with the highest average rating.

- "Shining stars" refers to episodes that are both highly viewed and highly rated;
- "Surfing the waves of popularity and acclaim" refers to achieving high rankings in both viewership and ratings;
- "Top 10 for viewership" means the 10 episodes with the highest total viewership;
- "Top 5 for ratings" means the 5 episodes with the highest average ratings.

- A season can be considered an episode in this hierarchy;
- The level indicates the depth of the episode in the hierarchy, where the top-level episodes (not belonging to any season) have a level of 1;
- The order by clause arranges the episodes first by their level in the hierarchy and then by their names.

- Top 5 episodes are determined by the highest average review ratings and the number of reviews;
- Series are ranked by the average rating of their episodes and the number of episodes they have;
- Episodes and series are matched based on their respective ranks.

sql:
SELECT MAX(viewers_millions) AS peak_audience_size
FROM viewing_statistics
WHERE platform = 'TV';

